observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Verify/check the amounts in liquidation reports submitted to the Provincial Accountant of fund transfers with discrepancies in the balance recorded in the books of the Province;
Determine the status of liquidations of unsettled fund transfers reflected in the books of the Province that has been fully liquidated in the books of the Municipality, and if necessary, provide the Provincial Accountant of copies of liquidation documents that have been submitted so that the unrecorded settlement will be taken up in the books of the Province;
Cause the reconciliation of the inter-agency payable account Due to LGUs of the Municipality with that of the reciprocal receivable account Due from LGUs of the Province, and effect the necessary adjusting entries on the variance noted to reflect the correct balances of said accounts; and
Conduct a periodic reconciliation of inter-agency reciprocal accounts to ensure accurate balances of payable/receivable accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to the following:
impose or set a timeline in determining the possibility of retrieval of documents supporting the dormant accounts;

if supporting documents could not be retrieved, initiate request for write-off in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005; and,

for active accounts, regular verification, analysis and validation of the receivables and fund transfers be made to facilitate the timely collectability and liquidation/settlement of the same.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
regularly provide the Provincial Accountant with data on the Province’s share in the real property and other tax collections made by the Municipality;

remit the valid current due Province’s share in real property and other taxes which remained unremitted by the Municipality;

trace the details of the fund transfers by requesting copies of Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) of the Province; and

submit liquidation documents for fund transfers recorded by the Province as receivable from the Municipality.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
for the PPEs under Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment, Sports Equipment and Other Machineries and Equipment, the Head of the Inventory Committee determine from the accounting records the period of the recorded transactions by going through prior years’ records and noting actual period of occurrence;
the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant retrieve relevant records to determine corresponding transactions in (a);
a physical inventory-taking of PPE items under  Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment, Sports Equipment and Other Machineries and Equipment classifications be conducted on the results of (a) and (b); 
subsequently, corresponding adjustments shall be made in both the property and accounting records; and,
for items which were not recorded in the accounting records, a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) be drawn to adjust the account balances in the books of accounts, if warranted, in order to reflect accurate amounts in the financial statements.

